{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608646/1957111201/1064.xml":{"full_text":"A-18\nTHE EVENING STAR, Washington. D. C.\nTUESDAY. KOVISm It. IWI\nT Business\nJ \u2014m-.\u2014\u2014m\u2014. -e_~\u2014\nCoca-Cola Chief Sees\nIncomes Beating Prices\nBy DONALD B. HADLEY\nOne of America\u2019s top businessmen today predicted a good\nyear in 1958. with personal incomes more than offsetting gains\nin the cost of living.\nIn the keynote address at the 39th national convention of the\nAmerican Bottlers of Carbonated Beverages. William E. Rob\ninson. president of the Coca-Cola Company, cited several\nreasons for this optimistic out-\nlook; growth in personal in- 1\ncome; expected reversal of the\ndecline in home construction; a\npromising year for new car\nsales: a larger supply of capital\nIn the open market, and. there\nfore, a possible upswing in\n\u2022pending by State and local gov.\nernments for public improve\nments.\n\u201cWith respect to the present j\ncondition of the American econ\nomy,\u2019\u2019 Mr. Robinson said, \u201cIj\nthink we have a basis for op\ntimism as far as our particular\nbusiness is concerned. Indeed,!\nI think we have a basis for op\ntimism with respect to the\nwhole consumer goods category\nof business.\u201d\n\u201cIn trying to envisage to\nmorrow, we have two major\nelements to consider: The\npresent and near future con\ndition of the American busi\nness,\u201d he said.\nWith respect to the present\ncondition of the American\neconomy, I think we have a\nbasis for optimism as far as\nour particular business is con\ncerned. Indeed, I think we have\na basis for optimism with re\nspect to the whole consumer\ngoods category of business.\n\"First, despite spots of unem\nployment in certain segments\nof industry\u2014due to the decline\nin capital expenditures the\nAmerican people will, I believe,\nin 1958, achieve the highest\nlevel of personal income they\nhave yet realized.\u201d\n\u201cThe cost of living had in\ncreased 3.4 per cent while the\ngrowth in personal Income was\n5.6 per cent so far in 1957,\u201d he\ndeclared.\n\u201cThere is every indication\nnow that the decline in home\nbuilding construction, which\nhas been constant in 1957, may\nbe reversed in 1958.\n\u201cSince the automobile is 1\nsuch an important segment of\nour economy, it will have an\neffect on the total picture in\n1958. which I believe will be\nfavorable. The dealer sales of\n1957 models for August, Sep\ntember and October were con\nsiderably beyond the industry's\nexpectation and his stocks of\n1957 models are in a healthy\ncondition. The foundations for\na good automobile year in 1958\nare present, providing only one\nthing, and that is that the pub\nlic will like the new 1958\nmodels.\n\"Lower capital demands for\nIndustrial capital goods should\nbring a larger supply of capi\ntal into the open market and\ntbis should result in easier\nmoney rates during 1958.\nLarger Capital Cuppl.v,\nLower Rates, eForerast\n\u201cThis improved capital sup-\nMUTUAL FUNDS\nNEW YORK- Nov. r: \u2014National\nAssociation Securities Dealer*. Inc.\n(Noon Quotation*)\nHid Asked\nAberdeen Fund I*4 ISW\nAffiliated Fund 5 26 5.6\u00bb\nAm Business Shra 352 .1.76\nAm Mutual Fund 7.08 7.47\nAssoc buna Trust 1.26 J :;o\nAtom Dev Mutual 4 4 64\nAxe Houghton Fd A 4 6X 5.00\nAxe Hough;on Fd B H hm 7 26\nAxe Houghton Btk Fd __ .I\u2019M .1 .Vi\nAxe Bcience A; El U 92 0.80\nBlue Ridge Mutual HH.i 10.78\nBoston Fund 14.4a 15.601\nBroad Street Invest IX5.') -114\nBullock Fund Jo 68 11.6<\u00bb\nCanada Gen Fund HUW 1177\nCanadian Fund 15 70 17.0 n\nCentury Shrs Trust ___ 10 71 21.ai\nChemical Fund 15 05 JH 28\nColonial Fund X IX x xx\nComwlth Investment 7.9 ft x. 67\nComwlth Stk Fund in so ll >4\nCons Invest Trust 15.62 17 12\nDe Ve*h Mut Fund 60 on 62 5o\nDelaware Fund 821 10.1 l\nElvers Grth Stk 561 615\nIvers Invest Fund 7,6.1 x 25\nDividend Shares 2.14 2.5 7\nDreyfus Fund 8.20 8.81\nEaton Ar How Bal 10.54 2n km\nEaton a* How Stk ]