und Canada 15 56 14 s*\u2019\nValue Line Fund 5 09 5 46\nValue Mne Income Fd 4 56 4 77\nWash Mutual Tmest 7.21 7 8x\nWellington Fund 11 75 17\u20189\nWhitehall Fund 10 75 11.62\n\u2022Net asset value\n|j|\nSvW\nManuscripts, Brief*,\nSpecification*\nand ALL ofhar iptcial eervictl\nSand for deicriptive folder\nply will also release a good\ndeal of postponed spending by\nStates and cities for badily\nneeded local improvements in\npublic building, roads, and par\nticularly schools.\u201d he added.\n\"We have had. of course, a\nrather drastic decline in stock\nmarket prices. Before the Sec\nond World War such a decline\nwould certainly have prophe\nsized a serious recession or\nmaybe a depression. Since the\nwar. however, in more cases\nthan hot, the stock market\naction has been behind and\nnot ahead of the news.\n\u201cNevertheless, this market\ndecline is bound to bring out\ncertain prophets of doom and\npessimism. Some of them are\nalready predicting an end to\nour prosperity and you may be\nsure that enemy propagandists\nall over the world will be pre\ndicting our crack-up. This\ncould produce a psychological\n1 recession by putting a dampen\ning and over-cautious blanket\n1 on the progressive outlook of\nthe American businessman.\n\u201cWith expanded productivtiy\nl nalmost every field, the com\npetition for the consumer dol\nlar will be more aggressive than\nin many years. In these cir\n-1 cumstances, he who hesitates\nmay not be lost, but he might\nget less of the consumer dollar\nthan he is entitled to.\n\u201cFor those who take an op\ntimistic positive view, and inten\nsify their advertising and pro\nmotional efforts, there should\nbe solid rewards.\u201d he said.\n\u201cWhat I have said is not a pre\ndiction. Rather, it is a strong\nconviction upon which we a;\nCoca-Cola are basing our plans\nand budget for 1958.\u201d\nD. C. Postal Receipts Lag\nBehind Election Year\nWashington postal receipts\nare lagging behind a year ago\nwhen the election boosted them\nto abnormally high levels, a re\nport from Postmaster Roy\nNorth disclosed today.\nOctober receipts totaled *2,-\n423.681. down 11.1 per cent\nfrom $2,725,786 in October last\nyear. The October total last\nyear Jumped 17 per cent above\na year earlier.\nTen months\u2019 receipts this\nyear amounted to *22.204.951.\na decrease of 2.3 per cent from\n$22,726,030 in the same 1956\nperiod.\nReceipts reflect rapid growth\nof the last decade. In October,\n1947, they totaled *1,500.660\nand the ten months\u2019 receipts\nthen amounted to $13,388,889.\nCapital Airlines Shows\nSmall September Net\nCapital Airlines yesterday re\nported net income of *71.307\nfor September and disclosed it\nhad reduced net loss for nine\nmonths of this year to $1,248,-\n861.\nThe September net compared\nwith $59,000 net profit reported\nfor September a year ago. The\nnine months\u2019 loss compared\nwith a net loss of $2,225,826 in\nthe same 1956 period,\nj The airline had a net loss of\n$478,920 for three months\nended September 30. compared\nwith a deficit of $1,291,239 a\nyear earlier.\nOperating revenues for the\nnine months rose to $65,888,399\nfrom $42,697,693 a year ago\ni and operating expenses ex\npanded to $68,558,345 from\n*47.406,339.\nCHI'GO LIVESTOCK\n1 CHICAGO. Nov l'i I h lUSDAI.\nSalable ho*s. JI.OOO, moderately ac\n:ive. weak to 25 lower on butcher*.\nt lose more active, only steady to 15\nlower; sows steady to 25 lower, decline\non weights over 400 lbs; good *hipping\n1 demand and all docal packers in trade.\n2-5 mixed grades l!in-2 7o lb buwner*\n16.X5-J7.15, most 250-270 m* 16X5-\n17.09. a few lots 5s moat weight* down\nto 16.75; a few hundred 1-2 190-225\nlb weights 17.25-1 7 50, over 250 head\nthese weight* mostly is ana most\nsorted loi grade 17.60. A desk :ts\naround 2X5 lbs 16 75. weights under\n200 lbs scarce, larger lots mixed\ngrade.s 560-525 lb sows 14 50-I.> 50.\na lew lots 525-.150 lbs 16.60*16.76.\n4EIAOIN NU ETAOIN NU NU NUNN\nSalable rattle X. 500: salable calves\n50o; slaughter steeis grading average\nchoice io low prime active; lully\nsteady to strong, other steers fully\nsteady; heifers steady lo strong; cows\nand bull* fully steady; vealers. Stock\ners and feeders unchanged; high\nchoice and prime steers 950-1.500 lor\ni 25,50-27.00; 2 leads 1.150 and 1.2X1\nlbs 27.25. bulk choice 24 50-25 50;\ngood and low choice 23.25-24 25; a\n.few standard to low good 19.00-23 00;\nhigh choice and prime heifers 24.50-\n25.00; a part load prime near 1.060\nlbs 26.00. good and choice 23 00-\n24 25; standard to low good 18 00-\nj 22.75: utility and commercial cows\n15 50-15 09; commercial and stand\nard 15 90-18 00 bulk canners and\ncutters 11 00-14 00: a few light shelly\ncanners down to 10.00 :uttlity end\n'commercial hulls 16 59-18 90 cutter\n1 bulls down to 14 50 and a few light\nfanners down to 13.50: good and\nchoice veslcr* 24.00-28 00: standard\ndown to 18 00: culls down to 12.00\u2019\n1 reveril loads holer 350-550 lb stock\nt steer calves ?600-\u2019\u00bb8 23; a few good\nand choice 23 00-25 00: two loads\n1 choice heifer calvee 22.75-23 nO\ni\nCOURTESY ECONOMY\" COMFORT\nmake every trip a pleasure trip\nSPEED\nCONVENIENCE HOSPITALITY\nWgW g L\nK M f g g g M g m M A\ni ROANOKE ASHEVILLE ~~7\u2122i\ntRISTOI-KINGSROIT-JOHNSON CITY FEjQ\nl___ ALSO Sarnie* to Knoxville, Huafiold, Lynchburg, tmmJLg-1\nand Chorlottaivill*. WW\nCALL DMrid 7-1100 il r\nOr Your Trov#l Agnnt\n\u25a0i M\nS m\nMANAGING EDITOR\u2014\nYates Catlin has been\nnamed managing editor\nI of the magazines World\nPorts and the Mariner,\nboth published by Amund\n-1 sen Publications, Inc.\nSince 1950 he has been\npublic relations director\nfor American Waterways\nI Operators.\n\nExperts Differ\nWidely on 'SB\nTrade Outlook\n\nA panel discussion of the\nj 1957 business outlook here lias\nfocused attention on the di-\nI j vergence of opinions among\neconomists.\nAddressing the annual meet-\nI ing of the National Lumber\nManufacturers Association at\nthe Shoreham Hotel, Ralph\nRobey, economic adviser 6f the\nNational Association of Manu\nfacturers, yesterday predicted\n1 a tax cut will cause an eco\nnomic upturn in 1958.\n1 Emerson P. Schmidt, eco\nnomic research director of the\nUnited States Chamber of\nCommerce, suggested that \"1958\nwill not be as good as 1957,\u201d\nalthough the \u201clong-range fac\ntors for expansion continue\nI strong.\u201d\nHerbert Stein, research direc\n-1 tor of the Committee for Eco\nnomic Development, predicted\nthe economy will continue at\nits present level for the next\nseveral months, \u201cprobably for\nmost of 1958.\u201d\nNathaniel Rogg, director of\nthe economics department ot\nf the National Association of\nHome Builders, predicted \u201clittle\ni change\u201d in the volume of home\nbuilding next year compared\nwith 1957. and estimated hous\ning starts in 1958 at \"close to\nthe one million level.\u201d\nExpects Further Rise\nMr. Robey said he sees \u201can\nother month or so\u201d of increases\nin the consumer price index\u2014\ni certainly'no decline before Jan\nuary, if them. He described the\ni economy as \u201cmoving sideways\u201d\ni at the present time and said it\nmust soon \u201cbreak out either on\ni the upside or the downside.\nMr. Schmidt said the econo-\nI my is \u201coverdue for a down\ni turn\u201d and is \u201cin for more than\na rolling adjustment.\u201d The\nUnited States Chamber spokes\nman asserted that a rise in un\nemployment\u2014to four or five\nmillion this winter\u2014is \"inevi\ntable\u201d and that business profits\nwill be \u201csqueezed seriously\u201d in\n1958. Further, he predicted\n1958 will see a \"good deal of\nprice cutting\u2014both announced\nand unannounced.\u201d he added:\nMr. Stein said an important\nfactor in the economy is the\nsteady growth in State and\nlocal government expenditures\nwhich \"shows no sign of abat\ning.\u201d On the home building\nfront, he said a two-year de\n-1; cline in housing starts \u201cshows\n1 signs of being reversed.\u201d\nMr. Stein said he expects the\nj Nation's total production of\ngoods and services in 1958 to\ncontinue at \u201cabout the pres\nent level.\u201d with the chances\nof a downturn greater than\nthe prospects of a rise.\nMortgage Funds to Ease\nMr. Rogg said he see no\nchange in new home prices\nduring 1958 but an easing in\ni the availability of mortgage\nfunds later in the year.\nAssuming that the rest of the\neconomy remains \"tolerably\ngood,\" the home building vol\n-1 ume in 1958 will total about\none million starts, with rental\nunits accounting for a larger\nshare of the market than in\ni j 1957, he asserted.\n_ 1 111\n1\nFor Rent\nTwo All Purpose\nBuildings\nStoned 2nd commercial. Ap\nproximately 10,000 sq. ft. May\nbe rented separately. Approx\nimately 5.000 aq. ft. each bldg.\nFireproofed. All mode rn.\nBrick. Vicinity North Capitol\nI and New York Ave. Available\n1 last of October.\nPLENTY OK PARKING SrACK\nAVAILABLE\nToll V 4. 8-207* or\nOs.. 4-2113\nY\u00b0m A\nMONEY'S WORTH W\nIT SYLVIA POUTER\nNo Time for Buyers\" Strike\n\u201cVery Personal\u201d were the\nwords underlined on the face\nof the envelope I found under\nmy door when I came home\nfrom work the other evening.\nThe letter was from a \u201cneigh\nbor\u201d who identified herself only\nas a \"simple housewife.\" She\nwrote that she has been read\ning my column \u201calmost reli\ngiously for several years\u201d and\nwas now appealing to me di\nrectly because lately, she ac\ncused, \u201cSylvia Porter has been\nspeaking from both sides of her\nmouth at the same time.\"\nThe implication of the rest of\nher intelligently written letter\nwas that in recent months, I\nhave been reporting simultane\nously about the depressing fac\ntors in our economy and the\nclimb in living costs to all-time\npeaks\u2014two seemingly contra\ndictory trends indeed.\nWhat needs \u201ctelling and re\ntelling,\u201d she continued, is \u201cthat\nthe problem of inflation is the\none we have to lick\u201d and it is\n\u201cup to the buying public\u201d to\nlick it.\nAnd she ended, \u201cPlease tell\nour i*eople to ask prices and\n.pointedly to refuse to buy too\n.'highly priced items, no matter\nhow badly they seem to be\nneeded. Let's stop buying\neven the highly priced foods\nand furniture and clothing, etc.\n\u2014until merchants are forced to\nreason.\u201d\nMy neighbor undoubtedly re\nflects the resentment of mil\nlions of Americans against to\nday\u2019s record-high prices and\nit's a resentment that, as a\nworking woman and housewife,\nI share to the fullest extent.\nMy Neighbor\u2019s suggestion\nthat I keep emphasizing that\ninflation is our fundamental\nproblem, I also acknowledge as\nwarranted. I believe inflation\nis the great economic challenge\nof our century.\nBut neither she nor any one\nelse will get support from me\nfor a buyers\u2019 strike now not\nin this crucial month of No\nvember, 1957.\nNow the forces pulling us\ntoward downtrend in 1958 are\nas powerful if not more\ni powerful than the forces\npulling us toward a new busi\nness advance. As 1957 moves\nto a close, we\u2019re clinging pre-\nI cariously to a narrow ledge\nbetween deflation and inflation.\nAnd what is the stimulant\nwhich, above all other stimu*-\nlants, can keep us from slipping\ninto deflation in 1958? It is:\nContinued strong buying by\ni us. America\u2019s consumers.\nIf we, America\u2019s consumers,\npull back now if we go in\nfor massive resistance to buying\nany food, clothing, furniture,\nappliances, etc., etc., we don\u2019t\nabsolutely need well turn\ntoday's slowdown into a slump\nin a matter of weeks.\nIf we follow my neighbor's\nurging and \"stop buying\nuntil merchants are forced to\nreason.\u201d we\u2019ll force them \u201cto\nreason\u201d fast. We\u2019ll also force\ncountless numbers of them into\nbankruptcy, we\u2019ll send jobless\nn%Tis%\nAverogt Annual Yield\nYOUR CAPITAL PROTECTED\nAGAINST LOSS\nFixed Yialdt\nNan-Fluctuating\nCath Profit! Paid Monthly\ninvestments Start at 12.500\nFor Fret Brochure Visit or Phone\nMASON MORTGAGE\nINVESTMENT CORP.\nSuit. non. BIT 15th St. tt.w.\nWashincton 6. D. C. Dlstriet 7-3465\nDevelopment!\nCommercial\nResidential\nApartment!\nConstruction\nFHA Loans\nMortgage Leant\nPreparty Management\nInsurant\nB. F. Saul Co*\n925 15th Stropt N.W.\nI NAtional 1-2100\ni ness skyrocketing, we\u2019ll create\na general crash.\nAnd if we follow this course,\nwe\u2019ll do even more. We\u2019ll\nguarantee the very runaway\ninflation we\u2019re trying so des\nperately to avert. For then,\ni the Government will put out\nevery anti-depression weapon\nwe have in our arsenal. We\u2019ll\nI go in for pump-priming and\nj turning of the printing presses\n!on a scale dwarfting anything\nlever seen in our land.\nWhen we get done, we will\nhave gone through an utterly;\nneedless depression and we will\nhave given inflation a gigantic\npush. Doesn\u2019t make much\nsense, does it?\nBut if i we continue to buy\nsteadily both for cash and on\nthe cuff, our spending by itself\nwill be an immense prop under\nour economy in 1958. Our\nspending and such other sac-\nI I tors as increased building of\ni houses and of roads will help\noffset the depressing factors,\nwill help pull us out of this\nI letdown\nI j Certainly, shop carefully,\np, check prices, look for bargains.\ncold-shoulder the profiteers.\nThat\u2019s obvious common sense\nin an era when the Consumer\ni is King.\nBut at a time when the cost\ni of living finally is leveling off\nand the economy is shivering\nfrom some chilly winds, it\nwould be folly for us to force\na slump by going on a buyers\u2019\nI stroke.\n(Distributed ifIST by The Hall\nSyndicate. Inc All Rights Reserved)\ni\nSurgeons Assemble\nHONOLULU. Nov. 12 (AV\n-1 Surgeons from far corners of\nthe world are arriving for the\n1 seventh Pan-Pacific Surgical\nAssociation congress which\nopens Thursday. At least 22\ncountries will be represented by\nsome 1,000 delegates.\n\u201cSt. Joseph Aspirin For Chi